article.description: Rookie Seimone Augustus scored a season-high 26 points and the Lynx broke the WNBA record for points in a game with a 114-71 victory over the Sparks.
article.headline: Augustus powers Lynx's 114-71 rout of Sparks
article.linkText: Augustus powers Lynx's 114-71 rout of Sparks
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- The Minnesota Lynx struggled to score in three straight losses. It was a completely different story Wednesday night against the Los Angeles Sparks.

Rookie Seimone Augustus scored a season-high 26 points to lead six players in double figures as the Lynx dominated on offense and set a WNBA scoring record in a 114-71 victory. Minnesota surpassed the previous record of 111 points, set by Detroit on June 18, 2000, against Indiana.

"I just caught myself shaking my head a couple times just watching them," Lynx coach Suzie McConnell Serio said. "This team tonight was fun to watch."

Augustus, who has carried most of the scoring load this season, finally got some help from her teammates to help Minnesota get its first win of the season -- and in convincing fashion.

Kristen Mann scored a career-high 18 points for the Lynx, who tied a league record with 15 3-pointers on 22 attempts. Augustus and Mann were both 4-for-5 from beyond the arc, while Svetlana Abrosimova was 5-for-5. Abrosimova scored a season-high 21 points on 8-for-9 shooting.

"We have a lot of scorers on our team and we play very unselfish basketball," Mann said. "I think we're capable of doing it again."

The 43-point margin of victory was the largest in franchise history, easily surpassing the previous best of 27 points against San Antonio on July 25, 2003. Minnesota fell just two points shy of tying the league record for largest margin of victory, set by the Houston Comets in 1998.

Tamara Moore scored 18 points to lead the road-weary Sparks, while Lisa Willis added 12.

Los Angeles caught a 5 a.m. flight from Chicago on Wednesday to play the second game of a back-to-back set, and its fifth straight road game to start the season.

"Everybody's kind of in a twilight zone when they came to the game," coach Joe Bryant said. "Minnesota had three or four days off, so they had more energy."

Added Lisa Leslie: "You saw a shell of a team out there."

The Lynx held Leslie to a season-low eight points -- all in the second quarter. Leslie came in leading the league with 23.8 points and 13.3 rebounds per game.

She left with 5:25 left in the third quarter after picking up her fifth foul and never returned.

"We wanted to attack her and make her work," Lynx center Nicole Ohlde said. "It was just a bonus that she got in foul trouble."

Meanwhile, the Lynx scored a franchise-record 51 points on 42.3 percent shooting in the first half, only to top that mark with 63 points in the second half. Minnesota scored 33 in the third quarter alone, also a season best. For good measure, the Lynx set team records with 34 field goals made and 29 assists.

"We knew one day everything was going to come together and from that point on we would gain momentum," Augustus said. "I'm glad it finally came."

Augustus got off to a quick start, scoring 11 first-quarter points to get the Lynx out to an eight-point lead. Minnesota then went on a 10-0 run early in the second quarter to build a 16-point advantage and never looked back.

Augustus scored six points during a 14-0 third quarter Lynx run before sitting out the fourth quarter. The closest Los Angeles came was 15 points, when Minnesota led 51-36 before the 14-0 run.
